The logs are actually very revealing.

What we know

At 09:41:57 SM started disabling every platform service:

cert-alarm
cert-mon
docker-distribution
etcd
postgres
rabbit
sysinv
keystone
vim
...

This is a platform shutdown sequence, not an individual service failure.

Then in sysinv.log:

09:42:02 Caught SIGTERM, stopping children
09:42:02 Stopping WSGI server
09:42:02 Child exited with status 0

So sysinv was gracefully terminated by SIGTERM, not crashed.

Also immediately before the shutdown:

09:41:12 All Kubernetes endpoints are healthy.

Therefore:

Kubernetes was healthy.

etcd was healthy.

Services did not fail themselves.

Something instructed SM to stop the service group.



---

The missing piece

The actual trigger is usually in one of these logs:

/var/log/sm.log
/var/log/sm-api.log
/var/log/mtcAgent.log
/var/log/mtcClient.log
/var/log/nfv-vim.log

Search around the timestamp:

grep -B50 -A50 "09:41:57" /var/log/sm.log

and

grep -iE "lock|unlock|swact|disable|active|standby|shutdown|reboot" /var/log/sm.log


---

Check if controller was locked/swacted

grep -iE "lock|swact" /var/log/mtcAgent.log

grep -iE "lock|swact" /var/log/mtcClient.log

grep -iE "swact|active|standby" /var/log/nfv-vim.log


---

Most likely scenario

The pattern:

All services disabled
sysinv receives SIGTERM
No service failures before disable

is typical of:

1. Controller lock


2. Controller reboot


3. Swact (active → standby)


4. Host services disable command



rather than:

etcd crash ❌

rabbit crash ❌

postgres crash ❌

Kubernetes failure ❌



---

Run this first

grep -B20 -A50 "09:41:57" /var/log/sm.log

and

grep -iE "swact|lock|disable|shutdown|reboot" /var/log/sm.log | tail -100

The sm-service.log only shows the effect (services being disabled). The actual reason is usually recorded in sm.log, and that should tell us whether it was a host lock, swact, reboot, or an administrative disable.
